This problem is really nice because the sum of an arithmetic progression (AP) is well-known. And the first five positive odd integers forms an AP with a difference of 2.
• Then, let’s look at the formula for an AP sum: \begin{align*} sum &= \frac{n(a_1+a_n)}{2}
with n=5, a_1=1, and an=9, where an is the last number of the AP. Then, \begin{align*} sum &= \frac{5(1+9)}{2}\\ &= \frac{5*10}{2}\\ &= \boxed{25} \end{align*}
Final Answer: The final answer is 25. I hope it is correct.  ### Solution video: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=bQVzOdOL1gg&list=PLAaw1oQt1AtzSQdR87go3bJuuwIB2p4f7 Extra: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=wrY39Sb2EXo&list=PLAaw1oQt1AtzSQdR87go3bJuuwIB2p4f7
